msub><mml:mi>X</mml:mi><mml:mrow><mml:mi mathvariant="italic">exp</mml:mi></mml:mrow></mml:msub><mml:mo>-</mml:mo><mml:msub><mml:mi>X</mml:mi><mml:mrow><mml:mi mathvariant="italic">sim</mml:mi></mml:mrow></mml:msub><mml:mrow><mml:mo stretchy="false">)</mml:mo></mml:mrow></mml:mrow><mml:mn>2</mml:mn></mml:msup><mml:mo>+</mml:mo><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">Σ</mml:mi><mml:mfrac><mml:mrow><mml:mo stretchy="false">(</mml:mo><mml:msup><mml:mrow><mml:msub><mml:mover><mml:mrow><mml:mi mathvariant="italic">MW</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mo>¯</mml:mo></mml:mover><mml:mrow><mml:mi mathvariant="italic">exp</mml:mi></mml:mrow></mml:msub><mml:mo>-</mml:mo><mml:msub><mml:mover><mml:mrow><mml:mi mathvariant="italic">MW</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mo>¯</mml:mo></mml:mover><mml:mrow><mml:mi mathvariant="italic">sim</mml:mi></mml:mrow></mml:msub><mml:mrow><mml:mo stretchy="false">)</mml:mo></mml:mrow></mml:mrow><mml:mn>2</mml:mn></mml:msup></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mi>M</mml:mi><mml:msubsup><mml:mi>W</mml:mi><mml:mrow><mml:mi mathvariant="italic">max</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mn>2</mml:mn></mml:msubsup></mml:mrow></mml:mfrac></mml:mrow></mml:math><graphic xlink:href="13321_2022_627_Article_Equ2.gif" position="anchor"/></alternatives></disp-formula></p>
      <p id="Par15">Here, we included the number average MW of the population (<inline-formula id="IEq14"><alternatives><tex-math id="M31">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${\overline{MW} }_{sim}$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M32"><mml:msub><mml:mover><mml:mrow><mml:mi mathvariant="italic">MW</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mo>¯</mml:mo></mml:mover><mml:mrow><mml:mi mathvariant="italic">sim</mml:mi></mml:mrow></mml:msub></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="13321_2022_627_Article_IEq14.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula>) if the experimental value (<inline-formula id="IEq15"><alternatives><tex-math id="M33">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${\overline{MW} }_{exp}$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M34"><mml:msub><mml:mover><mml:mrow><mml:mi mathvariant="italic">MW</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mo>¯</mml:mo></mml:mover><mml:mrow><mml:mi mathvariant="italic">exp</mml:mi></mml:mrow></mml:msub></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="13321_2022_627_Article_IEq15.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula>) is available. To ensure a similar scale ([0-1]), we divide the MW by the upper bound (<inline-formula id="IEq16"><alternatives><tex-math id="M35">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$M{W}_{max}$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M36"><mml:mrow><mml:mi>M</mml:mi><mml:msub><mml:mi>W</mml:mi><mml:mrow><mml:mi mathvariant="italic">max</mml:mi></mml:mrow></mml:msub></mml:mrow></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="13321_2022_627_Article_IEq16.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula>, set as 10,000 Da). The optimization minimizes <inline-formula id="IEq17"><alternatives><tex-math id="M37">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$d$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M38"><mml:mi>d</mml:mi></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="13321_2022_627_Article_IEq17.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula>, i.e., makes the simulated population as similar to the experiments as possible.</p>
      <p id="Par16">We first optimize a single polymer molecule by repeatedly adding monomers (linkages), as shown in the inner optimization loop in Additional file <xref rid="MOESM1" ref-type="media">1</xref>: Fig. S4. The monomer type, the linkage type, or the branching state for addition are sampled from the experimental distributions, following the rules described in the Polymerization section (Additional file <xref rid="MOESM1" ref-type="media">1</xref>: Fig. S5). For instance, for an experimental G:S ratio of 6:4 with no H present, the probability of adding a G and S monomer is 60% and 40%, respectively. Each event is accepted depending on the Metropolis criterion using <inline-formula id="IEq18"><alternatives><tex-math id="M39">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\Delta {d}_{i}$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M40"><mml:mrow><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">Δ</mml:mi><mml:msub><mml:mi>d</mml:mi><mml:mi>i</mml:mi></mml:msub></mml:mrow></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="13321_2022_627_Article_IEq18.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> (Additional file <xref rid="MOESM1" ref-type="media">1</xref>: Note 2). The polymer growth stops when the number of iterations or the polymer size is reached. The latter is sampled from a normal distribution and is expressed by the MW (<inline-formula id="IEq19"><alternatives><tex-math id="M41">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${{MW}_{i}}_{stop}$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M42"><mml:msub><mml:mrow><mml:msub><mml:mrow><mml:mi mathvariant="italic">MW</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mi>i</mml:mi></mml:msub></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mi mathvariant="italic">stop</mml:mi></mml:mrow></mml:msub></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="13321_2022_627_Article_IEq19.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula>, if the experimental value is available) or the number of monomers (<inline-formula id="IEq20"><alternatives><tex-math id="M43">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${{n}_{i}}_{stop}$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M44"><mml:msub><mml:mrow><mml:msub><mml:mi>n</mml:mi><mml:mi>i</mml:mi></mml:msub></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mi mathvariant="italic">stop</mml:mi></mml:mrow></mml:msub></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="13321_2022_627_Article_IEq20.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula>) (Additional file <xref rid="MOESM1" ref-type="media">1</xref>: Table S1). Next, we optimize the entire population (Fig. <xref rid="Fig4" ref-type="fig">4</xref>), shown as the outer optimization loop in Additional file <xref rid="MOESM1" ref-type="media">1</xref>: Fig. S4. Optimized polymers from the inner loop are added one at a time, based on the Metropolis criterion using <inline-formula id="IEq21"><alternatives><tex-math id="M45">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\Delta d$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M46"><mml:mrow><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">Δ</mml:mi><mml:mi>d</mml:mi></mml:mrow></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="13321_2022_627_Article_IEq21.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula>. Once 100 molecules have been added, or the maximum number of iterations is reached, we fine-tune linkages distributions by adding possible rings as intramolecular linkages (optimization loop in Additional file <xref rid="MOESM1" ref-type="media">1</xref>: Fig. S4). Several hyperparameters in the framework, such as the Metropolis temperature, the branching propensity, and the expected polymer size, can be tuned to speed up convergence. A complete list can be found in Additional file <xref rid="MOESM1" ref-type="media">1</xref>: Table S2.</p>
